    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA75-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu cēṭpaṭukkappaṭṭu āṟṟāṉāya talaivaṉ (EN: āṟṟāṉākiya; EN, EV: talaimakaṉ) tōḻi kēṭpac (ET: tōḻikkuc; ETv: tōḻikkut talaivi kēṭpac) colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is HE, who could not bear it to be kept at a distance, said while the confidante was listening.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA75">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nayaṉiṉ maiyiṟ payaṉitu veṉṉātu</l>
<l>            pūmpoṟip polinta vaḻalumi ḻakaṉpaip</l>
<l>            pāmpuyi raṇaṅki yāṅku mīṅkitu</l>
<l>            takāatu vāḻiyō kuṟumaka ṇakāa</l>
<l>            turaimati yuṭaiyumeṉ ṉuḷḷañ cāraṟ </l>
<l>            koṭuviṟ kāṉavaṉ kōṭṭumā tolaiccip</l>
<l>            paccūṉ peyta pakaḻi pōlac</l>
<l>            cēyari paranta vāyitaḻ maḻaikka</l>
<l>            ṇuṟāa nōkka muṟṟaveṉ</l>
<l>            paita ṉeñca muyyu māṟē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Without [even] saying “this [is] gain, in the absence of longing”,</l>
<l rend="indent">[wounding me] like<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">yāṅkum</term>: all the mss./editions (including Nacc. on TP 103 who quotes this poem) read unanimously this strange <term xml:lang="ta">-um</term> attached to the comparative particle. It does not make sense.</note> the lethal wound of the snake, gently,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with fire-spitting interior, glittering with flower[-like] spots,</l>
<l>this here is not fit, may you live, little woman.</l>
<l>Talk [to me] without smiling,</l>
<l>in a way that my suffering heart will survive,</l>
<l rend="indent"><choice>
    <seg>which had a look at</seg> 
    <seg>which had a side-glance<note place="foot">There is clearly a playful intention in the <term xml:lang="ta">uṟāa -- uṟṟa</term>. The point might either be that he can have a look at, but not possess the object of desire herself. Or <term xml:lang="ta">uṟāa</term> qualifies the glance, as is understood by T.V.G.: a glance that is not a direct glance.</note></seg>
</choice>
    ,[however] without having</l>
<l rend="indent">[her of] rain eyes with choice lashes spread with red lines,</l>
<l rend="indent2">like arrows pulled(?) from the fresh flesh,</l>
<l rend="indent3">after the forest men with bent bows</l>
<l rend="indent3">have killed the boar on the slope,</l>
<l rend="indent4">in my breaking mind.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṭaiyum eṉ uḷḷam</term> poses a bit of a syntactical problem. Its relations to the rest of the poem are totally unmarked. T.V.G. wants to read it as another independent sentence ('My mind breaks.'), but then it would have to be taken as an insertion, because the <term xml:lang="ta">māṟu</term> clause must be dependent on the <term xml:lang="ta">uraimati</term>.</note></l>
        </lg>
         </div>
